    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{5}{3b}+\frac{1}{2b}}={-2}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{\frac{-13}{12}\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{6b}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{5}{3b}+\frac{1}{2b}} \amp = {-2} \\
  {\frac{5}{3b}\cdot 6b+\frac{1}{2b}\cdot 6b} \amp = {-2\cdot 6b} \\
  10+3 \amp = {-12b} \\
  13 \amp = {-12b} \\
  \frac{13}{-12} \amp = \frac{{-12b}}{-12} \\
  {\left\{\frac{-13}{12}\right\}} \amp = b \\
  b \amp  = {\left\{\frac{-13}{12}\right\}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>b \ne 0</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>b = {\left\{\frac{-13}{12}\right\}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
